<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="407" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,620,645]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is originated from the word Jo’bel (“zacate grande”), used by pre ‒ Hispanic people when referring to the 
<collectingCountry box="[475,627,655,680]" name="Saint Kitts and Nevis" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">San Cristóbal</collectingCountry>
de las Casas valley in 
<collectingRegion box="[882,976,655,680]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="407" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,692,717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is known from three close localities in the Altos de 
<collectingRegion box="[1133,1223,692,717]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
region, inside the 
<collectingRegion box="[151,241,727,752]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
province (
<emphasis box="[364,382,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">s.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Morrone" box="[391,558,727,752]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407" refString="Morrone, J. (2005) Hacia una sintesis biogeografica de Mexico. Revista Mexicana de Biodiversidad, 76 (2), 207 - 252." type="journal article" year="2005">Morrone 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Its distribution may be related to pine-oak and tropical montane rain forests from this province (
<figureCitation box="[373,457,764,789]" captionStart="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[514,1092,1007,1817]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[470,1116,949,1856]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57 — Map of collecting localities for Colletes jobeli, C. isabelae, C. jaliscoensis and C. nigerrima. 58 — Map of collecting localities for C. solari, C. tzotzilis, C. chiaPensis, and C. guatemalensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1051949/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="407" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,799,824]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Remarks.</emphasis>
Females may have dark mandibles, reduced notch on clypeus margin, and opaque terga (probably deterioration). Some females may have malar area three times wider than longer. In males, the notch on distal margin of clypeus may be reduced and the margins of terga may be brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
